content.thinking:
Now the components. ProgressHeader, Flashcard (3D flip), ActionBar, CompletionState. Then ReviewPage.

ProgressHeader: shows title + remaining/total + known count. Semantic IDs: review-progress-total, review-progress-remaining, review-progress-known.

Flashcard: tap to flip, 3D rotateY. Semantic IDs: review-flashcard, review-card-front-word, review-card-back-meaning, review-card-back-phonetic.

ActionBar: 认识 / 不认识 buttons. IDs review-known-button, review-unknown-button.

CompletionState: review-empty-state, review-restart-button.

For the 3D flip in ArkUI, I'll use rotate with angle state and two children (front/back). Use animateTo on tap. Swap visible face at midpoint.

Approach: Stack containing both front and back. 
- front: visible when !showBack, rotate angle 0->180
- back: visible when showBack, rotate angle 180->360 (i.e. starts at 180)

Simplest robust: single Stack, one child whose content swaps based on showBack, and the whole thing rotates rotateY from 0 to 180 (or back). When flipping forward, animate angle 0->180; at 90° set showBack=true. When flipping back, animate 180->0; at 90° set showBack=false.

To avoid mid-animation content pop, use two faces. Let me do two-face:

```
Stack() {
  // Front face
  Column() { ... front ... }
    .visibility(this.angle < 90 ? Visibility.Visible : Visibility.Hidden)
    .rotate({ x:0, y:1, z:0, angle: this.angle })
  // Back face - pre-rotated 180 so its text isn't mirrored
  Column() { ... back ... }
    .visibility(this.angle >= 90 ? Visibility.Visible : Visibility.Hidden)
    .rotate({ x:0, y:1, z:0, angle: this.angle + 180 })
}
```

Wait, when angle is between 90 and 180, front should be hidden, back shown. Back face rotate = angle + 180 means at angle=90, back rotates 270 (i.e. -90, showing edge)... hmm. Standard CSS 3D flip: back is pre-rotated rotateY(180deg) and we rotate container 0->180. In ArkUI each child has its own rotate, no backface-visibility. Let me think with container approach:

Container rotates 0->180. Inside: front child normal, back child pre-rotated 180. We toggle which child is "in front" via z-order/visibility at midpoint. But rotating each child independently:

- front child rotate angle = containerAngle (0->180). Visible when containerAngle <= 90.
- back child rotate angle = containerAngle - 180. At containerAngle=180, back rotate=0 (correct, readable). At containerAngle=90, back rotate=-90 (edge, invisible-ish). Visible when containerAngle > 90.

So:
```
front.rotate({angle: this.angle, y:1})  visible if angle <= 90
back.rotate({angle: this.angle - 180, y:1})  visible if angle > 90
```

At angle=0: front rotate 0 (visible, readable), back rotate -180 (hidden). Good.
At angle=90: front rotate 90 (edge, hidden), back rotate -90 (edge, hidden). Transition.
At angle=180: front rotate 180 (hidden), back rotate 0 (visible, readable). Good.

This works. Use animateTo to transition angle 0<->180. Toggle at midpoint isn't even needed since visibility is a function of angle and updates each frame? Actually Visibility is a discrete prop, ArkUI won't re-evaluate it during animation frame-by-frame unless it's bound to the animating @State. During animateTo, the animating value is the @State angle itself, and `.visibility(this.angle <= 90 ? Visible : Hidden)` — ArkUI evaluates property expressions once per build; during animation it animates the rendered transform but the visibility expression... Hmm, this is tricky. ArkUI animateTo animates properties that are explicitly set via the state. visibility changes mid-animation may not trigger reliably.

Safer approach: swap showBack via setTimeout at midpoint (half of duration). Let me do that — it's reliable and widely used.

```
@State angle: number = 0;
@State showFront: boolean = true;

private flip(): void {
  if (this.animating) return;
  this.animating = true;
  const goingToBack = this.showFront;
  animateTo({ duration: 400, curve: Curve.EaseInOut, onFinish: () => { this.animating = false; } }, () => {
    this.angle = goingToBack ? 180 : 0;
  });
  setTimeout(() => { this.showFront = !goingToBack; }, 200);
}
```

Wait, if showFront controls which face renders, and we swap at 200ms (midpoint when angle=90, edge-on, content invisible), there's no visible pop. Good.

But rendering only one face means the rendered face rotates from 0->180. When showFront, front rotates 0->180 (ends mirrored). When we swap to back at midpoint, back should appear and continue to 0 readable. If back is a fresh child rendered at angle... the back child also gets `.rotate({angle: this.angle})`. At midpoint angle≈90, back rendered at 90 (edge, invisible) then animates to 180. But back at 180 is mirrored (text backwards)! So back child needs rotate = angle - 180 so at angle=180 it's rotate 0 (readable).

So:
```
if (this.showFront) {
  FrontFace().rotate({angle: this.angle, y:1, ...})
} else {
  BackFace().rotate({angle: this.angle - 180, y:1, ...})
}
```

Timeline flip forward (showFront true->false):
- t=0: showFront true, angle 0, front rotate 0 (readable)
- animate angle 0->180
- t=200ms: angle=90, showFront set false -> back face now rendered, back rotate = 90-180 = -90 (edge, invisible). Good, no pop.
- t=400: angle=180, back rotate=0 (readable). 

Flip backward (showFront false->true):
- angle goes 180->0
- t=0: showFront false, angle 180, back rotate 0 (readable)
- t=200: angle=90, showFront true -> front rotate=90 (edge). 
- t=400: angle=0, front rotate 0 (readable). 

This is correct and reliable. Let me implement.

Actually, simpler: since spec doesn't require both faces simultaneously, the swap-at-midpoint single-face approach is clean. Let me code it.

The Flashcard needs props: word, meaning, phonetic, isFlipped (controlled by parent? or internal?). The controller owns isFlipped. The page calls controller.flipCard() then updates @State isFlipped, and passes isFlipped + onFlip to Flashcard. Flashcard reacts to isFlipped changes to animate.

To trigger animation on isFlipped prop change, Flashcard can watch with @Prop and use aboutToAppear... Actually reacting to prop change with animation: use @Watch on the prop. Let me have Flashcard own the animation driven by @Prop isFlipped with @Watch.

Let me write Flashcard:
```ts
@Component
export struct Flashcard {
  @Prop word: string = '';
  @Prop meaning: string = '';
  @Prop phonetic: string = '';
  @Prop isFlipped: boolean = false;
  onTap: () => void = () => {};
  @State private angle: number = 0;
  @State private showFront: boolean = true;
  private animating: boolean = false;

  aboutToAppear(): void {
    this.angle = this.isFlipped ? 180 : 0;
    this.showFront = !this.isFlipped;
  }

  @Watch('isFlipped') onFlipChanged(): void {
    this.runFlip();
  }

  private runFlip(): void {
    const target = this.isFlipped ? 180 : 0;
    this.animating = true;
    animateTo({ duration: 400, curve: Curve.EaseInOut, onFinish: () => { this.animating = false; } }, () => {
      this.angle = target;
    });
    setTimeout(() => { this.showFront = !this.isFlipped; }, 200);
  }

  build() {
    Stack() {
      if (this.showFront) {
        this.FrontFace()
      } else {
        this.BackFace()
      }
    }
    ...
    .rotate({ x: 0, y: 1, z: 0, angle: this.angle, centerX: '50%', centerY: '50%' })
    .onClick(() => { if (!this.animating) this.onTap(); })
  }
}
```

Wait — the rotate must be applied differently per face. Front rotate = angle, back rotate = angle - 180. If I put rotate on the Stack and both faces share the stack, then I need per-face rotate. Let me put rotate on each face builder, not the stack.

Actually with single rendered face, I can put rotate on the face itself:
- FrontFace.rotate angle = this.angle
- BackFace.rotate angle = this.angle - 180

But .rotate is applied in the build chain. Let me structure:

```
build() {
  Stack() {
    if (this.showFront) {
      Column() {...front...}
        .rotate({x:0,y:1,z:0, angle: this.angle, centerX:'50%', centerY:'50%'})
    } else {
      Column() {...back...}
        .rotate({x:0,y:1,z:0, angle: this.angle - 180, centerX:'50%', centerY:'50%'})
    }
  }
  .onClick(...)
}
```

But animateTo animates @State angle; both branches use this.angle so animation works. But the rotate prop is set during build. When angle changes via animateTo, ArkUI re-renders and applies new rotate -> animates. Should work.

However there's a subtlety: when showFront flips at midpoint, the conditional rebuild happens. The newly-shown back Column gets rotate = angle-180. At that instant angle≈90 so back rotate≈-90. As animation continues to angle=180, back rotate animates to 0. Good.

Let me write the front and back faces with semantic IDs. front-word id: review-card-front-word. back: review-card-back-meaning, review-card-back-phonetic. The tap target: review-flashcard on the Stack.

Let me write ProgressHeader, ActionBar, CompletionState, Flashcard, ReviewPage.

For child-friendly, use emoji? The skill says: "Do not use emoji or pictographic Unicode as icons in ArkTS Text, tabs, buttons, pills, stats, summaries, or final UI." So NO emoji. Use plain text. Good — I'll avoid emoji.

